circa 1090","1062":"1062","Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Française":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Frankrijk","Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Frankrijk","Noyers, Avallon, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Frankrijk","Noyon, Compiègne, Oise, Picardie, France":"Noyon, Oise, Picardie, Frankrijk","Noyers,27445,Eure,Normandie,FRANCE,":"Noyers, Eure, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1056–1104":"1056–1104","1062–1104":"1062–1104","1080–1120":"1080–1120","1090–1126":"1090–1126","1034–1078":"1034–1078","1025–Female":"1025–Deceased","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1104":"1104","1126":"1126","1025":"1025","1056":"1056","1078":"1078","1034":"1034","1120":"1120","ABT 1090":"about 1090","1062":"1062","Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Française":"Noyers, Yonne, Burgundy, France","Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Burgundy, France","Noyers, Avallon, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Burgundy, France","Noyon, Compiègne, Oise, Picardie, France":"Noyon, Oise, Picardie, France","Noyers,27445,Eure,Normandie,FRANCE,":"Noyers, Eure, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Noyers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Meyer   1 or   Mayer  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Dutch: patronymic from   Moyer   3, or a variant of <b>Moyaers</b>, a nickname for a dandy, from a derivative of Middle Dutch <i>moy</i>, <i>moeie</i> ‘fine, handsome’.","Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Mac an Mhaoir</b> ‘son of the steward’, with English excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Meyer","meanings":["German and Swiss German: from Middle High German <i>meier</i>, a status name for a steward, bailiff, or overseer, which later came to be used also to denote a tenant farmer, which is normally the sense in the many compound surnames formed with this term as a second element. Originally it denoted a village headman (ultimately from Latin <i>maior</i> ‘greater, superior’). This form of the surname is also established in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine); see also 3 below. Compare   Maier  ,   Mayer  ,   Meier  , and   Myer  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish personal name <i>Meyer</i>, from Hebrew <i>Meir</i> ‘enlightener’, a derivative of <i>or</i> ‘light’ with the prefix <i>m-</i>. Compare   Maier  ,   Majer  ,   Major  ,   Mayer  ,   Mayor  ,   Meier  , and   Meir  .","Dutch: variant, also Flemish and Americanized, of   Meijer  , a cognate of 1 above. This surname is also established in South Africa, where it was also brought from France (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Milon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name from the numerous places so called, a large number of which get their name from Old English <i>mylentūn</i> ‘settlement with a mill’. Others were originally named as ‘the middle settlement (of three)’, from Old English <i>middel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. The surname is most famous as that of the poet  John Milton  (  1608–74 ), and the given name is sometimes bestowed in his honour. Its most illustrious bearer in recent times has been the economist  Milton Friedman  (  1912–2006 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Milon de Noyers II was born in 1056, in Noyers, Yonne, Burgundy, France, his father, Milo I de Noyers Sgr. de Noyers, was 23 and his mother, Agatha de Wallingford, was 31. He married Anna de Toucy in 1080, in Noyers, Yonne, Burgundy, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1104, in his hometown, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1056–1104":"1056–1104","1062–1104":"1062–1104","1080–1120":"1080–1120","1090–1126":"1090–1126","1034–1078":"1034–1078","1025–Female":"1025–Surnud","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1104":"1104","1126":"1126","1025":"1025","1056":"1056","1078":"1078","1034":"1034","1120":"1120","ABT 1090":"umbes 1090","1062":"1062","Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Française":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa","Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa","Noyers, Avallon, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa","Noyon, Compiègne, Oise, Picardie, France":"Noyon, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Noyers,27445,Eure,Normandie,FRANCE,":"Noyers, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1056–1104":"1056–1104","1062–1104":"1062–1104","1080–1120":"1080–1120","1090–1126":"1090–1126","1034–1078":"1034–1078","1025–Female":"1025–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1104":"1104","1126":"1126","1025":"1025","1056":"1056","1078":"1078","1034":"1034","1120":"1120","ABT 1090":"noin 1090","1062":"1062","Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Française":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Ranska","Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Ranska","Noyers, Avallon, Yonne, Bourgogne, France":"Noyers, Yonne, Bourgogne, Ranska","Noyon, Compiègne, Oise, Picardie, France":"Noyon, Oise, Picardie, Ranska","Noyers,27445,Eure,Normandie,FRANCE,":"Noyers, Eure, Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1056–1104":"1056–1104","1062–1104":"1062–1104","1080–1120":"1080–1120","1090–1126":"1090–1126","1034–1078":"1034–1078","1025–Female":"1025–Dé